Government policy can lower the cost of capital for clean investment through many mechanisms. For example, they can lower the cost of debt (interest rate firms pay) via concessional, lower-rate loans. They can offer credit guarantees to lower default risk. They can capitalize green banks that lower debt cost. Each of these approaches can lower cost of capital but have differing effects on actual borrowing rates. 
12,759,0,-1642,-2058,128,96,8,135,0,4,-1,0,0,0,-1--1--1,255-255-128,|||0-0-0,0,0,0,0,0,0
This section does not include policies that lower the cost of equity like offtake agreements, carbon contracts for difference, or investment/production subsidies. Nor policies that reduce percieved technology risk like demonstration grants/pilot funding. Nor those reducing macroeconomic risk like stable policy frameworks or carbon pricing with predictable forecasts. 
