These government and household spending variables are only used to determine the proportion of spending going to each ISIC code.  Therefore, the time series projection here is meant simply to reflect how growth or shrinkage of one ISIC code relative to another is reflected in (in reality, partially caused by) changes in government and household spending.  It does not matter whether these variables contain accurate absolute amounts spent, as they are not used for that purpose.
1,418,2,365,0,0,0,0,0,128,0,-1--1--1,,1|(0,0)|
1,419,364,365,0,0,0,0,0,128,0,-1--1--1,,1|(0,0)|
12,420,0,2608,391,243,88,8,135,0,4,-1,0,0,0,-1--1--1,255-255-128,|||0-0-0,0,0,0,0,0,0
There is no way to use projected output by ISIC code to obtain projected DLIM or TLIM variables.  In general, even if an industry gets larger or smaller in the future, it may need the same sorts of inputs (from its own and from other ISIC codes) to produce a unit of output.  These requirements can shift over time - for instance, an industry that today requires metal might someday require less metal but more plastic.  However, we can't get these sorts of shifts in what inputs industries need and on what they spend their money from changes in total output by that industry, or by other industries.  Therefore, we do not attempt to make time-series DLIM or TLIM variables.
12,421,0,3054,6,150,112,8,135,0,4,-1,0,0,0,-1--1--1,255-255-128,|||0-0-0,0,0,0,0,0,0
We assume that changes in output for each specific ISIC code are directly proportional to changes in employment, value added, and total employee compensation paid by that ISIC code.  Note that economy-wide shifts in these three metrics (not arising from growth or shrinkage of various ISIC codes, such as a tendency across all industries to pay workers more per hour worked) can be implemented through BPEaCP.  (See the "Time Series Totals" section later on this sheet.)
