Any tax revenue that is rebated to households or businesses (i.e. partial or total revenue neutrality) doesn't count toward the Total Change in CapEx and OpEx metric, so we subtract out any tax rebate payments here.
10,158,Change in Nonenergy Expenditures by Entity due to Production Changes,914,2804,75,30,8,130,0,3,-1,0,0,0,128-128-128,0-0-0,|||128-128-128,0,0,0,0,0,0
12,159,0,914,2715,288,68,8,135,0,4,-1,0,0,0,-1--1--1,255-255-128,|||0-0-0,0,0,0,0,0,0
Changes in purchases of non-energy input materials (e.g. raw steel, etc.) are also a part of OpEx, but at present, we don't separate out input materials from other industrial products - we only have the total change in expenditures on all industrial products in variable "Changes in Nonenergy Expenditures by Entity due to Production Changes."  Including this entire variable in the cost metric tends to overwhelm other components of the cost metric when material efficiency policies are enabled.  For now, we exclude changes in spending on input materials from the CapEx + OpEx metric.  We may revisit this in a future EPS update.
12,160,0,2280,1947,205,47,8,135,0,4,-1,0,0,0,-1--1--1,255-255-128,|||0-0-0,0,0,0,0,0,0
This variable is no longer used in the cost metric (because we now subtract out the portion of government revenue change allocated to tax reduction/rebates for revenue neutrality, instead of assuming the total of every tax and subsidy is revenue-neutral), but we leave the calculations here in case they are useful later.
